     A prototype of QuoteMachine, a user-facing tool built by AFP‚Äôs Arnaud Pichon and Fred Bourgeais.
    <i>Photograph: QuoteMachine</i>
    </figcaption>
    </figure>
<p>Chris Moran, the head of editorial innovation at the Guardian, says: ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre committed to thinking about AI and automation through a journalistic lens, and will be experimenting as much as we can to find the really positive ways we can apply it and avoid the pitfalls.‚Äù</p>
<p>Attempting to identify and extract quotes from news articles using ML may seem arcane to some. But the potential benefits to readers, journalists and editors could be considerable ‚Äì from making sure we are giving a platform to those who are often under-represented, to building products and formats that tell the whole story, rather than defaulting to a simple ‚Äúhe said, she said‚Äù formula.</p>
<p>Watch this space, we hope to update you on our progress soon.</p>
<p><em>This project is part of the <a href="https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/polis/2021/03/23/journalismai-collab-challenges/">2021 JournalismAI Collab Challenges</a>, a global initiative that brings together media organisations to explore innovative solutions to improve journalism via the use of AI technologies. It was developed as part of the EMEA cohort of the Collab Challenges that focused on modular journalism with the support of <a href="https://bbcnewslabs.co.uk/">BBC News Labs</a> and <a href="https://clwstwr.org.uk/">Clwstwr</a>.</em></p>
